# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: music-generation-ai
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] Algorithms (or, at the very least, formal sets of rules) have been used to compose music for centuries; the procedures used to plot voice-leading in Western counterpoint, for example, can often be reduced to algorithmic determinacy.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] The term can be used to describe music-generating techniques that run without ongoing human intervention, for example through the introduction of chance procedures.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] However through live coding and other interactive interfaces, a fully human-centric approach to algorithmic composition is possible.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] Some algorithms or data that have no immediate musical relevance are used by composers as creative inspiration for their music.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] Algorithms such as fractals, L-systems, statistical models, and even arbitrary data (e.g. census figures, GIS coordinates, or magnetic field measurements) have been used as source materials.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] Compositional algorithms are usually classified by the specific programming techniques they use.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] The results of the process can then be divided into 1) music composed by a computer and 2) music composed with the aid of a computer.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] Music may be considered composed by a computer when the algorithm is able to make choices of its own during the creation process.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] Another way to sort compositional algorithms is to examine the results of their compositional processes.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] Algorithms can either 1) provide notational information (sheet music or MIDI) for other instruments or 2) provide an independent way of sound synthesis (playing the composition by itself).
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] There are also algorithms creating both notational data and sound synthesis.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] This is an approach to music synthesis that involves "translating" information from an existing non-musical medium into a new sound.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] The translation can be either rule-based or stochastic.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] For example, when translating a picture into sound, a JPEG image of a horizontal line may be interpreted in sound as a constant pitch, while an upwards-slanted line may be an ascending scale.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] Oftentimes, the software seeks to extract concepts or metaphors from the medium, (such as height or sentiment) and apply the extracted information to generate songs using the ways music theory typically represents those concepts.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] Mathematical models are based on mathematical equations and random events.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] The most common way to create compositions through mathematics is stochastic processes.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] In stochastic models a piece of music is composed as a result of non-deterministic methods.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] The compositional process is only partially controlled by the composer by weighting the possibilities of random events.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] Prominent examples of stochastic algorithms are Markov chains and various uses of Gaussian distributions.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] Stochastic algorithms are often used together with other algorithms in various decision-making processes.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] Music has also been composed through natural phenomena.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] These chaotic models create compositions from the harmonic and inharmonic phenomena of nature.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] For example, since the 1970s fractals have been studied also as models for algorithmic composition.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] As an example of deterministic compositions through mathematical models, the On-Line Encyclopedia of Integer Sequences provides an option to play an integer sequence as 12-tone equal temperament music.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] (It is initially set to convert each integer to a note on an 88-key musical keyboard by computing the integer modulo 88, at a steady rhythm.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] Thus 123456, the natural numbers, equals half of a chromatic scale.) As another example, the all-interval series has been used for computer-aided composition.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] One way to create compositions is to isolate the aesthetic code of a certain musical genre and use this code to create new similar compositions.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] Knowledge-based systems are based on a pre-made set of arguments that can be used to compose new works of the same style or genre.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] Usually this is accomplished by a set of tests or rules requiring fulfillment for the composition to be complete.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] Music can also be examined as a language with a distinctive grammar set.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] Compositions are created by first constructing a musical grammar, which is then used to create comprehensible musical pieces.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] Grammars often include rules for macro-level composing, for instance harmonies and rhythm, rather than single notes.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] When generating well defined styles, music can be seen as a combinatorial optimization problem, whereby the aim is to find the right combination of notes such that the objective function is minimized.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] This objective function typically contains rules of a particular style, but could be learned using machine learning methods such as Markov models.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] Researchers have generated music using a myriad of different optimization methods, including integer programming, variable neighbourhood search, and evolutionary methods as mentioned in the next subsection.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] Evolutionary methods of composing music are based on genetic algorithms.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] The composition is being built by the means of evolutionary process.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] Through mutation and natural selection, different solutions evolve towards a suitable musical piece.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] Iterative action of the algorithm cuts out bad solutions and creates new ones from those surviving the process.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] The results of the process are supervised by the critic, a vital part of the algorithm controlling the quality of created compositions.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] Evolutionary methods, combined with developmental processes, constitute the *evo-devo* approach for generation and optimization of complex structures.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] These methods have also been applied to music composition, where the musical structure is obtained by an iterative process that transform a very simple composition (made of a few notes) into a complex fully-fledged piece (be it a score, or a MIDI file).
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] Learning systems are programs that have no given knowledge of the genre of music they are working with.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] Instead, they collect the learning material by themselves from the example material supplied by the user or programmer.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] The material is then processed into a piece of music similar to the example material.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] This method of algorithmic composition is strongly linked to algorithmic modeling of style, machine improvisation, and such studies as cognitive science and the study of neural networks.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] Assayag and Dubnov proposed a variable length Markov model to learn motif and phrase continuations of different length.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] Marchini and Purwins presented a system that learns the structure of an audio recording of a rhythmical percussion fragment using unsupervised clustering and variable length Markov chains and that synthesizes musical variations from it.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] Programs based on a single algorithmic model rarely succeed in creating aesthetically satisfying results.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] For that reason algorithms of different type are often used together to combine the strengths and diminish the weaknesses of these algorithms.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] Creating hybrid systems for music composition has opened up the field of algorithmic composition and created also many brand new ways to construct compositions algorithmically.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] The only major problem with hybrid systems is their growing complexity and the need of resources to combine and test these algorithms.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] Another approach, which can be called *computer-assisted composition*, is to algorithmically create certain structures for finally "hand-made" compositions.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] As early as in the 1960s, Gottfried Michael Koenig developed computer programs *Project 1* and *Project 2* for aleatoric music, the output of which was sensibly structured "manually" by means of performance instructions.
[src:music-generation-ai/algorithmic-composition] In the 2000s, Andranik Tangian developed a computer algorithm to determine the time event structures for rhythmic canons and rhythmic fugues, which were then worked out into harmonic compositions *Eine kleine Mathmusik I* and *Eine kleine Mathmusik II*; for scores and recordings see.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] In machine learning, **diffusion models**, also known as **diffusion-based generative models** or **score-based generative models**, are a class of latent variable generative models.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] A diffusion model consists of two major components: the forward diffusion process, and the reverse sampling process.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] The goal of diffusion models is to learn a diffusion process for a given dataset, such that the process can generate new elements that are distributed similarly as the original dataset.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] A diffusion model models data as generated by a diffusion process, whereby a new datum performs a random walk with drift through the space of all possible data.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] A trained diffusion model can be sampled in many ways, with different efficiency and quality.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] There are various equivalent formalisms, including Markov chains, denoising diffusion probabilistic models, noise conditioned score networks, and stochastic differential equations.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] They are typically trained using variational inference.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] The model responsible for denoising is typically called its "backbone".
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] The backbone may be of any kind, but they are typically U-nets or transformers.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] As of 2024, diffusion models are mainly used for computer vision tasks, including image denoising, inpainting, super-resolution, image generation, and video generation.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] These typically involve training a neural network to sequentially denoise images blurred with Gaussian noise.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] The model is trained to reverse the process of adding noise to an image.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] After training to convergence, it can be used for image generation by starting with an image composed of random noise, and applying the network iteratively to denoise the image.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Diffusion-based image generators have seen widespread commercial interest, such as Stable Diffusion and DALL-E.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] These models typically combine diffusion models with other models, such as text-encoders and cross-attention modules to allow text-conditioned generation.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Other than computer vision, diffusion models have also found applications in natural language processing such as text generation and summarization, sound generation, and reinforcement learning.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Diffusion models were introduced in 2015 as a method to train a model that can sample from a highly complex probability distribution.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] They used techniques from non-equilibrium thermodynamics, especially diffusion.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Consider, for example, how one might model the distribution of all naturally occurring photos.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] A model that can approximately undo the diffusion can then be used to sample from the original distribution.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] This is studied in "non-equilibrium" thermodynamics, as the starting distribution is not in equilibrium, unlike the final distribution.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] This is just the Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution of particles in a potential well $V(x)={\frac {1}{2}}\|x\|^{2}$ at temperature 1.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] The initial distribution, being very much out of equilibrium, would diffuse towards the equilibrium distribution, making biased random steps that are a sum of pure randomness (like a Brownian walker) and gradient descent down the potential well.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] The randomness is necessary: if the particles were to undergo only gradient descent, then they will all fall to the origin, collapsing the distribution.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] The 2020 paper proposed the Denoising Diffusion Probabilistic Model (DDPM), which improves upon the previous method by variational inference.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] To present the model, some notation is required.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] The values of $\beta _{t}$ are chosen such that for any starting distribution of $x_{0}$ , if it has finite second moment, then $\lim _{t\to \infty }x_{t}|x_{0}$ converges to ${\mathcal {N}}(0,I)$ .
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] In particular, we note that $x_{1:T}|x_{0}$ is a Gaussian process, which affords us considerable freedom in reparameterization.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] That is, after a long enough diffusion process, we end up with some $x_{T}$ that is very close to ${\mathcal {N}}(0,I)$ , with all traces of the original $x_{0}\sim q$ gone.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] We also know that these are independent.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] There are 5 variables ${\textstyle x_{0},x_{t-1},x_{t},z,z'}$ and two linear equations.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] The two sources of randomness are ${\textstyle z,z'}$ , which can be reparameterized by rotation, since the IID Gaussian distribution is rotationally symmetric.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] By plugging in the equations, we can solve for the first reparameterization: $x_{t}={\sqrt {{\bar {\alpha }}_{t}}}x_{0}+\underbrace {{\sqrt {\alpha _{t}-{\bar {\alpha }}_{t}}}z+{\sqrt {1-\alpha _{t}}}z'} _{=\sigma _{t}z''}$ where ${\textstyle z''}$ is a Gaussian with mean zero and variance one.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] The key idea of DDPM is to use a neural network parametrized by $\theta$ .
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] To do that, we use maximum likelihood estimation with variational inference.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] This allows us to perform variational inference.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Define the loss function $L(\theta ):=-E_{x_{0:T}\sim q}[\ln p_{\theta }(x_{0:T})-\ln q(x_{1:T}|x_{0})]$ and now the goal is to minimize the loss by stochastic gradient descent.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Now we see that estimating $x_{0}$ is equivalent to estimating z .
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] The DDPM paper suggested not learning it (since it resulted in "unstable training and poorer sample quality"), but fixing it at some value $\Sigma _{\theta }(x_{t},t)=\zeta _{t}^{2}I$ , where either $\zeta _{t}^{2}=\beta _{t}{\text{ or }}{\tilde {\sigma }}_{t}^{2}$ yielded similar performance.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] The paper noted empirically that an even simpler loss function $L_{simple,t}=E_{x_{0}\sim q;z\sim {\mathcal {N}}(0,I)}\left[\left\|\epsilon _{\theta }(x_{t},t)-z\right\|^{2}\right]$ resulted in better models.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Score-based generative model is another formulation of diffusion modelling.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] They are also called noise conditional score network (NCSN) or score-matching with Langevin dynamics (SMLD).
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Consider the problem of image generation.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Let x represent an image, and let $q(x)$ be the probability distribution over all possible images.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] If we have $q(x)$ itself, then we can say for certain how likely a certain image is.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] However, this is intractable in general.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Most often, we are uninterested in knowing the absolute probability of a certain image.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Instead, we are usually only interested in knowing how likely a certain image is compared to its immediate neighbors — e.g. how much more likely is an image of cat compared to some small variants of it?
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Is it more likely if the image contains two whiskers, or three, or with some Gaussian noise added?
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Consequently, we are actually quite uninterested in $q(x)$ itself, but rather, $\nabla _{x}\ln q(x)$ .
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Let the score function be $s(x):=\nabla _{x}\ln q(x)$ ; then consider what we can do with $s(x)$ .
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] As it turns out, $s(x)$ allows us to sample from $q(x)$ using thermodynamics.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Specifically, if we have a potential energy function $U(x)=-\ln q(x)$ , and a lot of particles in the potential well, then the distribution at thermodynamic equilibrium is the Boltzmann distribution $q_{U}(x)\propto e^{-U(x)/k_{B}T}=q(x)^{1/k_{B}T}$ .
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] At temperature $k_{B}T=1$ , the Boltzmann distribution is exactly $q(x)$ .
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] So no matter what distribution $x_{0}$ has, the distribution of $x_{t}$ converges in distribution to q as $t\to \infty$ .
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Given a density q , we wish to learn a score function approximation $f_{\theta }\approx \nabla \ln q$ .
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] This is **score matching***.* Typically, score matching is formalized as minimizing **Fisher divergence** function $E_{q}[\|f_{\theta }(x)-\nabla \ln q(x)\|^{2}]$ .
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] By expanding the integral, and performing an integration by parts, $E_{q}[\|f_{\theta }(x)-\nabla \ln q(x)\|^{2}]=E_{q}[\|f_{\theta }\|^{2}+2\nabla \cdot f_{\theta }]+C$ giving us a loss function, also known as the Hyvärinen scoring rule, that can be minimized by stochastic gradient descent.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Suppose we need to model the distribution of images, and we want $x_{0}\sim {\mathcal {N}}(0,I)$ , a white-noise image.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Now, most white-noise images do not look like real images, so $q(x_{0})\approx 0$ for large swaths of $x_{0}\sim {\mathcal {N}}(0,I)$ .
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] This presents a problem for learning the score function, because if there are no samples around a certain point, then we can't learn the score function at that point.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] If we do not know the score function $\nabla _{x_{t}}\ln q(x_{t})$ at that point, then we cannot impose the time-evolution equation on a particle: $dx_{t}=\nabla _{x_{t}}\ln q(x_{t})dt+dW_{t}$ To deal with this problem, we perform annealing.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] If q is too different from a white-noise distribution, then progressively add noise until it is indistinguishable from one.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] That is, we perform a forward diffusion, then learn the score function, then use the score function to perform a backward diffusion.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Now, the equation is exactly a special case of the overdamped Langevin equation $dx_{t}=-{\frac {D}{k_{B}T}}(\nabla _{x}U)dt+{\sqrt {2D}}dW_{t}$ where D is diffusion tensor, T is temperature, and U is potential energy field.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] This explains why the phrase "Langevin dynamics" is sometimes used in diffusion models.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Now the above equation is for the stochastic motion of a single particle.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Suppose we have a cloud of particles distributed according to q at time $t=0$ , then after a long time, the cloud of particles would settle into the stable distribution of ${\mathcal {N}}(0,I)$ .
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Let $\rho _{t}$ be the density of the cloud of particles at time t , then we have $\rho _{0}=q;\quad \rho _{T}\approx {\mathcal {N}}(0,I)$ and the goal is to somehow reverse the process, so that we can start at the end and diffuse back to the beginning.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] By Fokker-Planck equation, the density of the cloud evolves according to $\partial _{t}\ln \rho _{t}={\frac {1}{2}}\beta (t)\left(n+(x+\nabla \ln \rho _{t})\cdot \nabla \ln \rho _{t}+\Delta \ln \rho _{t}\right)$ where n is the dimension of space, and $\Delta$ is the Laplace operator.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] If we have solved $\rho _{t}$ for time $t\in [0,T]$ , then we can exactly reverse the evolution of the cloud.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] then by plugging into the Fokker-Planck equation, we find that $\partial _{t}\rho _{T-t}=\partial _{t}\nu _{t}$ .
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Thus this cloud of points is the original cloud, evolving backwards.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] That is, we can quickly sample $x_{t}\sim \rho _{t}$ for any $t\geq 0$ .
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] DDPM and score-based generative models are equivalent.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] This means that a network trained using DDPM can be used as a NCSN, and vice versa.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Thus, given a good score-based network, its predicted score is a good prediction of the noise (after scaling by $\sigma _{t}$ ), and thus can be used for denoising.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] In DDPM, the sequence of numbers $0=\sigma _{0}<\sigma _{1}<\cdots <\sigma _{T}<1$ is called a (discrete time) **noise schedule**.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] In general, consider a strictly increasing monotonic function $\sigma$ of type $\mathbb {R} \to (0,1)$ , such as the sigmoid function.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] In that case, a noise schedule is a sequence of real numbers $\lambda _{1}<\lambda _{2}<\cdots <\lambda _{T}$ .
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] In order to use arbitrary noise schedules, instead of training a noise prediction model $\epsilon _{\theta }(x_{t},t)$ , one trains $\epsilon _{\theta }(x_{t},\sigma _{t})$ .
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Similarly, for the noise conditional score network, instead of training $f_{\theta }(x_{t},t)$ , one trains $f_{\theta }(x_{t},\sigma _{t})$ .
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] The original DDPM method for generating images is slow, since the forward diffusion process usually takes $T\sim 1000$ to make the distribution of $x_{T}$ to appear close to Gaussian.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] However this means the backward diffusion process also take 1000 steps.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Unlike the forward diffusion process, which can skip steps as $x_{t}|x_{0}$ is Gaussian for all $t\geq 1$ , the backward diffusion process does not allow skipping steps.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Attempting to directly sample $x_{t-2}|x_{t}$ would require us to marginalize out $x_{t-1}$ , which is generally intractable.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] DDIM is a method to take any model trained on DDPM loss, and use it to sample with some steps skipped, sacrificing an adjustable amount of quality.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] If we generate the Markovian chain case in DDPM to non-Markovian case, DDIM corresponds to the case that the reverse process has variance equals to 0.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] In other words, the reverse process (and also the forward process) is deterministic.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] When using fewer sampling steps, DDIM outperforms DDPM.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] In detail, the DDIM sampling method is as follows.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] If all $\sigma _{s}'=0$ , then the backward process becomes deterministic, and this special case of DDIM is also called "DDIM".
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] The original paper noted that when the process is deterministic, samples generated with only 20 steps are already very similar to ones generated with 1000 steps on the high-level.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] The original paper recommended defining a single "eta value" $\eta \in [0,1]$ , such that $\sigma _{s}'=\eta {\tilde {\sigma }}_{s}$ .
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] When $\eta =1$ , this is the original DDPM.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] When $\eta =0$ , this is the fully deterministic DDIM.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] For intermediate values, the process interpolates between them.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] By the equivalence, the DDIM algorithm also applies for score-based diffusion models.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Since the diffusion model is a general method for modelling probability distributions, if one wants to model a distribution over images, one can first encode the images into a lower-dimensional space by an encoder, then use a diffusion model to model the distribution over encoded images.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Then to generate an image, one can sample from the diffusion model, then use a decoder to decode it into an image.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] The encoder-decoder pair is most often a variational autoencoder (VAE).
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] proposed various architectural improvements.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] For example, they proposed log-space interpolation during backward sampling.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] This parameterization was found to improve performance, as the model can be trained to reach total noise (i.e. $\phi _{t}=90^{\circ }$ ) and then reverse it, whereas the standard parameterization never reaches total noise since ${\sqrt {{\bar {\alpha }}_{t}}}>0$ is always true.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Classifier guidance was proposed in 2021 to improve class-conditional generation by using a classifier.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] The original publication used CLIP text encoders to improve text-conditional image generation.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Suppose we wish to sample not from the entire distribution of images, but conditional on the image description.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] We don't want to sample a generic image, but an image that fits the description "black cat with red eyes".
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Generally, we want to sample from the distribution $p(x|y)$ , where x ranges over images, and y ranges over classes of images (a description "black cat with red eyes" is just a very detailed class, and a class "cat" is just a very vague description).
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Taking the perspective of the noisy channel model, we can understand the process as follows: To generate an image x conditional on description y , we imagine that the requester really had in mind an image x , but the image is passed through a noisy channel and came out garbled, as y .
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Image generation is then nothing but inferring which x the requester had in mind.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] In other words, conditional image generation is simply "translating from a textual language into a pictorial language".
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Then, as in noisy-channel model, we use Bayes theorem to get $p(x|y)\propto p(y|x)p(x)$ in other words, if we have a good model of the space of all images, and a good image-to-class translator, we get a class-to-image translator "for free".
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] During the diffusion process, we need to condition on the time, giving $\nabla _{x_{t}}\ln p(x_{t}|y,t)=\nabla _{x_{t}}\ln p(y|x_{t},t)+\nabla _{x_{t}}\ln p(x_{t}|t)$ Although, usually the classifier model does not depend on time, in which case $p(y|x_{t},t)=p(y|x_{t})$ .
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] The classifier-guided diffusion model samples from $p(x|y)$ , which is concentrated around the maximum a posteriori estimate $\arg \max _{x}p(x|y)$ .
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] If we want to force the model to move towards the maximum likelihood estimate $\arg \max _{x}p(y|x)$ , we can use $p_{\gamma }(x|y)\propto p(y|x)^{\gamma }p(x)$ where $\gamma >0$ is interpretable as *inverse temperature*.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] In the context of diffusion models, it is usually called the **guidance scale**.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] A high $\gamma$ would force the model to sample from a distribution concentrated around $\arg \max _{x}p(y|x)$ .
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] This sometimes improves quality of generated images.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Note that for CFG, the diffusion model cannot be merely a generative model of the entire data distribution $\nabla _{x}\ln p(x)$ .
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] It must be a conditional generative model $\nabla _{x}\ln p(x|y)$ .
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] For example, in stable diffusion, the diffusion backbone takes as input both a noisy model $x_{t}$ , a time t , and a conditioning vector y (such as a vector encoding a text prompt), and produces a noise prediction $\epsilon _{\theta }(x_{t},y,t)$ .
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Also, if the unconditional generation $\epsilon _{\text{uncond}}\leftarrow \epsilon _{\theta }(x_{t},t)$ is replaced by $\epsilon _{\text{neg cond}}\leftarrow \epsilon _{\theta }(x_{t},t,c')$ , then it results in negative prompting, which pushes the generation away from $c'$ condition.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Given a diffusion model, one may regard it either as a continuous process, and sample from it by integrating a SDE, or one can regard it as a discrete process, and sample from it by iterating the discrete steps.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] The choice of the "**noise schedule**" $\beta _{t}$ can also affect the quality of samples.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] A noise schedule is a function that sends a natural number to a noise level: $t\mapsto \beta _{t},\quad t\in \{1,2,\dots \},\beta \in (0,1)$ A noise schedule is more often specified by a map $t\mapsto \sigma _{t}$ .
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] In the DDPM perspective, one can use the DDPM itself (with noise), or DDIM (with adjustable amount of noise).
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] The case where one adds noise is sometimes called ancestral sampling.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] One can interpolate between noise and no noise.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] The amount of noise is denoted $\eta$ ("eta value") in the DDIM paper, with $\eta =0$ denoting no noise (as in *deterministic* DDIM), and $\eta =1$ denoting full noise (as in DDPM).
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] In the perspective of SDE, one can use any of the numerical integration methods, such as Euler–Maruyama method, Heun's method, linear multistep methods, etc.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Just as in the discrete case, one can add an adjustable amount of noise during the integration.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] A survey and comparison of samplers in the context of image generation is in.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Notable variants include Poisson flow generative model, consistency model, critically damped Langevin diffusion, GenPhys, cold diffusion, etc.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] The probability path is in fact defined implicitly by the score function $\nabla \ln p_{t}$ .
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] In denoising diffusion models, the forward process adds noise, and the backward process removes noise.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Both the forward and backward processes are SDEs, though the forward process is integrable in closed-form, so it can be done at no computational cost.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] The backward process is not integrable in closed-form, so it must be integrated step-by-step by standard SDE solvers, which can be very expensive.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] The probability path in diffusions model is defined through an Itô process and one can retrieve the deterministic process by using the Probability ODE flow formulation.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] In flow-based diffusion models, the forward process is a deterministic flow along a time-dependent vector field, and the backward process is also a deterministic flow along the same vector field, but going backwards.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] If the vector field is well-behaved, the ODE will also be well-behaved.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] The solution $\phi _{t}$ of the above ODE define a probability path $p_{t}=[\phi _{t}]_{\#}\pi _{0}$ by the pushforward measure operator.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] The idea of **optimal transport flow** is to construct a probability path minimizing the Wasserstein metric.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] The idea of **rectified flow** is to learn a flow model such that the velocity is nearly constant along each flow path.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] This is beneficial, because we can integrate along such a vector field with very few steps.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] For example, if an ODE ${\dot {\phi _{t}}}(x)=v_{t}(\phi _{t}(x))$ follows perfectly straight paths, it simplifies to $\phi _{t}(x)=x_{0}+t\cdot v_{0}(x_{0})$ , allowing for exact solutions in one step.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] In practice, we cannot reach such perfection, but when the flow field is nearly so, we can take a few large steps instead of many little steps.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] The general idea is to start with two distributions $\pi _{0}$ and $\pi _{1}$ , then construct a flow field $\phi ^{0}=\{\phi _{t}:t\in [0,1]\}$ from it, then repeatedly apply a "reflow" operation to obtain successive flow fields $\phi ^{1},\phi ^{2},\dots$ , each straighter than the previous one.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] When the flow field is straight enough for the application, we stop.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] In rectified flow, by injecting strong priors that intermediate trajectories are straight, it can achieve both theoretical relevance for optimal transport and computational efficiency, as ODEs with straight paths can be simulated precisely without time discretization.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Specifically, rectified flow seeks to match an ODE with the marginal distributions of the **linear interpolation** between points from distributions $\pi _{0}$ and $\pi _{1}$ .
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] This process ensures that the trajectories closely mirror the density map of $x_{t}$ trajectories but *reroute* at intersections to ensure causality.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] A distinctive aspect of rectified flow is its capability for "**reflow**", which straightens the trajectory of ODE paths.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] This "reflow" process not only reduces transport costs but also straightens the paths of rectified flows, making $\phi ^{k}$ paths straighter with increasing k .
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] Rectified flow includes a nonlinear extension where linear interpolation $x_{t}$ is replaced with any time-differentiable curve that connects $x_{0}$ and $x_{1}$ , given by $x_{t}=\alpha _{t}x_{1}+\beta _{t}x_{0}$ .
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] This framework encompasses DDIM and probability flow ODEs as special cases, with particular choices of $\alpha _{t}$ and $\beta _{t}$ .
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] However, in the case where the path of $x_{t}$ is not straight, the reflow process no longer ensures a reduction in convex transport costs, and also no longer straighten the paths of $\phi _{t}$ .
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] These linear flow formulations were independently discovered and adapted from a different perspective for supervised inverse problems.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] For example, Inversion by Direct Iteration (InDI) formulates image restoration by learning a residual flow ODE that iteratively reverses a linear interpolation between a degraded input and a high-quality target to avoid regression-to-the-mean.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p01] InDI is effective for a variety of image restoration tasks.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] For generating images by DDPM, we need a neural network that takes a time t and a noisy image $x_{t}$ , and predicts a noise $\epsilon _{\theta }(x_{t},t)$ from it.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] Since predicting the noise is the same as predicting the denoised image, then subtracting it from $x_{t}$ , denoising architectures tend to work well.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] For example, the U-Net, which was found to be good for denoising images, is often used for denoising diffusion models that generate images.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] For DDPM, the underlying architecture ("backbone") does not have to be a U-Net.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] It just has to predict the noise somehow.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] For example, the diffusion transformer (DiT) uses a Transformer to predict the mean and diagonal covariance of the noise, given the textual conditioning and the partially denoised image.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] It is the same as standard U-Net-based denoising diffusion model, with a Transformer replacing the U-Net.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] Mixture of experts-Transformer can also be applied.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] DDPM can be used to model general data distributions, not just natural-looking images.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] For example, Human Motion Diffusion models human motion trajectory by DDPM.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] Each human motion trajectory is a sequence of poses, represented by either joint rotations or positions.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] It uses a Transformer network to generate a less noisy trajectory out of a noisy one.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] The base diffusion model can only generate unconditionally from the whole distribution.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] For example, a diffusion model learned on ImageNet would generate images that look like a random image from ImageNet.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] To generate images from just one category, one would need to impose the condition, and then sample from the conditional distribution.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] Whatever condition one wants to impose, one needs to first convert the conditioning into a vector of floating point numbers, then feed it into the underlying diffusion model neural network.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] However, one has freedom in choosing how to convert the conditioning into a vector.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] Stable Diffusion, for example, imposes conditioning in the form of cross-attention mechanism, where the query is an intermediate representation of the image in the U-Net, and both key and value are the conditioning vectors.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] The conditioning can be selectively applied to only parts of an image, and new kinds of conditionings can be finetuned upon the base model, as used in ControlNet.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] As a particularly simple example, consider image inpainting.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] The conditions are ${\tilde {x}}$ , the reference image, and m , the inpainting mask.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] Another application of cross-attention mechanism is prompt-to-prompt image editing.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] Conditioning is not limited to just generating images from a specific category, or according to a specific caption (as in text-to-image).
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] For example, demonstrated generating human motion, conditioned on an audio clip of human walking (allowing syncing motion to a soundtrack), or video of human running, or a text description of human motion, etc.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] For how conditional diffusion models are mathematically formulated, see a methodological summary in.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] As generating an image takes a long time, one can try to generate a small image by a base diffusion model, then upscale it by other models.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] Upscaling can be done by GAN, Transformer, or signal processing methods like Lanczos resampling.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] Diffusion models themselves can be used to perform upscaling.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] Cascading diffusion model stacks multiple diffusion models one after another, in the style of Progressive GAN.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] The lowest level is a standard diffusion model that generate 32x32 image, then the image would be upscaled by a diffusion model specifically trained for upscaling, and the process repeats.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] This section collects some notable diffusion models, and briefly describes their architecture.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] The DALL-E series by OpenAI are text-conditional diffusion models of images.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] The first version of DALL-E (2021) is not actually a diffusion model.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] Instead, it uses a Transformer architecture that autoregressively generates a sequence of tokens, which is then converted to an image by the decoder of a discrete VAE.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] Released with DALL-E was the CLIP classifier, which was used by DALL-E to rank generated images according to how close the image fits the text.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] GLIDE (2022–03) is a 3.5-billion diffusion model, and a small version was released publicly.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] DALL-E 2 is a 3.5-billion cascaded diffusion model that generates images from text by "inverting the CLIP image encoder", the technique which they termed "unCLIP".
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] The unCLIP method contains 4 models: a CLIP image encoder, a CLIP text encoder, an image decoder, and a "prior" model (which can be a diffusion model, or an autoregressive model).
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] During training, the prior model is trained to convert CLIP image encodings to CLIP text encodings.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] The image decoder is trained to convert CLIP image encodings back to images.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] During inference, a text is converted by the CLIP text encoder to a vector, then it is converted by the prior model to an image encoding, then it is converted by the image decoder to an image.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] Sora (2024–02) is a diffusion Transformer model (DiT).
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] LTX is a family of open source artificial intelligence video foundation models developed by Lightricks, first released in November 2024.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] The latest models, LTX-2, create videos based on user prompts, conditioned on text, images, video or audio - and capable of generating audio and visual in a unified way.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] They were preceded by LTX Video, which was released in 2024 as the company's first text-to-video model.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] Stable Diffusion (2022–08), released by Stability AI, consists of a denoising latent diffusion model (860 million parameters), a VAE, and a text encoder.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] The denoising network is a U-Net, with cross-attention blocks to allow for conditional image generation.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] Stable Diffusion 3 (2024–03) changed the latent diffusion model from the UNet to a Transformer model, and so it is a DiT.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] Stable Video 4D (2024–07) is a latent diffusion model for videos of 3D objects.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] Imagen (2022) uses a T5-XXL language model to encode the input text into an embedding vector.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] It is a cascaded diffusion model with three sub-models.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] The first step denoises a white noise to a 64×64 image, conditional on the embedding vector of the text.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] The second step upscales the image by 64×64→256×256, conditional on embedding.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] The three denoising networks are all U-Nets.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] Muse (2023–01) is not a diffusion model, but an encoder-only Transformer that is trained to predict masked image tokens from unmasked image tokens.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] Imagen 2 (2023–12) is also diffusion-based.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] It can generate images based on a prompt that mixes images and text.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] Veo (2024) generates videos by latent diffusion.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] The diffusion is conditioned on a vector that encodes both a text prompt and an image prompt.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] Make-A-Video (2022) is a text-to-video diffusion model.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] CM3leon (2023) is not a diffusion model, but an autoregressive causally masked Transformer, with mostly the same architecture as LLaMa-2.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] Transfusion (2024) is a Transformer that combines autoregressive text generation and denoising diffusion.
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] Specifically, it generates text autoregressively (with causal masking), and generates images by denoising multiple times over image tokens (with all-to-all attention).
[src:music-generation-ai/diffusion-model-p02] Movie Gen (2024) is a series of Diffusion Transformers operating on latent space and by flow matching.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] The prevalence of generative AI tools has increased significantly since the AI boom in the 2020s.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] This boom was made possible by improvements in deep neural networks, particularly large language models (LLMs), which are based on the transformer architecture.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI applications include chatbots such as ChatGPT, Claude, Copilot, DeepSeek, Doubao, Google Gemini, Grok and Qwen; text-to-image models such as DALL-E, Firefly, Stable Diffusion, and Midjourney; and text-to-video models such as Veo, LTX and Sora.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Companies in a variety of sectors have used generative AI, including those in software development, healthcare, finance, entertainment, customer service, sales and marketing, art, writing, and product design.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI has been used for cybercrime, and to deceive and manipulate people through fake news and deepfakes.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI models have been trained on copyrighted works without the rightholders' permission.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Many generative AI systems use large-scale data centers, whose environmental impacts include electronic waste, consumption of fresh water for cooling, and high energy consumption that is estimated to be growing steadily.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] The origins of algorithmically generated media can be traced to the development of the Markov chain, which has been used to model natural language since the early 20th century.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Russian mathematician Andrey Markov introduced the concept in 1906, including an analysis of vowel and consonant patterns in *Eugene Onegin*.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Once trained on a text corpus, a Markov chain can generate probabilistic text.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] By the early 1970s, artists began using computers to extend generative techniques beyond Markov models.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Harold Cohen developed and exhibited works produced by AARON, a pioneering computer program designed to autonomously create paintings.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] The terms generative AI planning or generative planning were used in the 1980s and 1990s to refer to AI planning systems, especially computer-aided process planning, used to generate sequences of actions to reach a specified goal.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI planning systems used symbolic AI methods such as state space search and constraint satisfaction and were a "relatively mature" technology by the early 1990s.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] They were used to generate crisis action plans for military use, process plans for manufacturing and decision plans such as in prototype autonomous spacecraft.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Machine learning uses both discriminative models and generative models to predict or generate data.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Beginning in the late 2000s and early 2010s, advances in deep learning led to major improvements in image classification, speech recognition, and natural language processing.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Neural networks in this period were typically trained as discriminative models due to the relative difficulty of training generative models.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2014, the introduction of models such as the variational autoencoder (VAE) and generative adversarial network (GAN) enabled effective deep generative modeling of complex data such as images.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2017, the Transformer architecture enabled further advances in generative modeling compared to earlier long short-term memory (LSTM) networks.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] This led to the development of generative pre-trained transformer (GPT) models, beginning with GPT-1 in 2018.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] In March 2020, the release of 15.ai, a free web application created by an anonymous MIT researcher that could generate convincing character voices using minimal training data, was one of the earliest publicly available uses for generative AI.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] The platform is credited as the first mainstream service for audio deepfakes.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2021, DALL-E, a closed-source transformer-based generative model developed by OpenAI, drew widespread attention to text-to-image generation.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Other projects, including open-source approaches such as VQGAN+CLIP and DALL·E Mini (later renamed Craiyon), made similar systems more accessible to the public.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Dream by Wombo was released at the end of 2021, followed by the releases of Midjourney and Stable Diffusion in 2022.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] In November 2022, ChatGPT was released to the public.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] By 2023, it popularized generative AI for general-purpose text-based tasks.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] In a 2024 survey by marketing research firm Ipsos, Asia–Pacific countries were significantly more optimistic than Western societies about generative AI and show higher adoption rates.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Despite expressing concerns about privacy and the pace of change, 68% of Asia-Pacific respondents believed that AI was having a positive impact on the world, compared to 57% globally.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] According to a survey by SAS and Coleman Parkes Research, as of 2023, 83% of Chinese respondents were using the technology, exceeding both the global average of 54% and the U.S. rate of 65%.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] A UN report indicated that Chinese entities filed over 38,000 generative AI patents from 2014 to 2023, more than any other country.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] A 2024 survey by the Just So Soul social media app reported that 18% of respondents born after 2000 used generative AI "almost every day", and that over 60% of respondents like or love AI-generated content (AIGC), while less than 3% dislike or hate it.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative artificial intelligence has been applied across multiple industries for content creation and automation.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] In healthcare, generative models are used for drug discovery and the generation of synthetic medical data to train diagnostic systems.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] In finance, they are used for report drafting, data generation, and customer service automation.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Media and entertainment industries use generative systems for tasks such as music composition, script development, and image or video generation.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Researchers and policymakers have raised concerns regarding accuracy, misuse, and impacts on academic and professional work.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Large language models (LLMs) are trained on tokenized text from large corpora and are capable of natural language processing, machine translation, and natural language generation.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] LLMs can be used as foundation models for a variety of downstream tasks.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] They can also be trained on source code to generate programs from prompts.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2016, DeepMind's WaveNet demonstrated that deep neural networks can generate raw audio waveforms.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] This enabled more realistic speech synthesis compared to earlier approaches.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Subsequent systems such as Tacotron 2 demonstrated end-to-end neural text-to-speech generation.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI can be used to create visual art.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Such systems are trained on image–text pairs.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Examples include Stable Diffusion, DALL-E, and Midjourney.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI can be used to produce photorealistic videos.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Systems such as Runway have demonstrated text-to-video generation capabilities.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative models can be used for motion planning and robot control by learning from prior data.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative models can assist in automating 3D modeling tasks, including generating 3D assets from text or images.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] World models are neural networks designed to learn representations of physical environments, including spatial and dynamic properties.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Recent multimodal systems have expanded these capabilities by integrating vision, language, and action into unified models.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI systems have been used in mathematics and computer science to generate candidate computer programs, proofs, constructions, or algorithms.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2023, Google DeepMind introduced FunSearch, a method for creating computer programs that solve mathematical and algorithmic problems.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] FunSearch was used to discover new mathematical constructions in the cap set problem and the bin packing problem.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2023, Google DeepMind introduced AlphaDev, which was used to discover small sorting algorithms that outperformed previously known human benchmarks and have been integrated into the LLVM standard C++ sorting library.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2025, Google DeepMind introduced AlphaEvolve, an AI system for general-purpose algorithm discovery and optimization.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] AlphaEvolve uses LLMs to propose code changes, automated evaluators to assess each candidate, and an evolutionary process to iteratively improve algorithms.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2023, Google DeepMind introduced GNoME, a method to propose candidate inorganic crystal structures for computational screening and experimental synthesis in material science.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Other material science methods include MatterGen, CDVAE, and CrystalFlow.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative engine optimization (GEO) is the practice of structuring digital content and managing online presence to improve visibility in responses generated by generative AI systems.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] The practice influences the way large language models (LLMs) retrieve, summarize, and present information in response to user queries.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Related terms include answer engine optimization (AEO) and artificial intelligence optimization (AIO).
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI models are used to power chatbot products such as ChatGPT, programming tools such as GitHub Copilot, text-to-image products such as Midjourney, and text-to-video products such as Runway Gen-2.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI features have been integrated into a variety of existing commercially available products such as Microsoft Office (Microsoft Copilot), Google Photos, and the Adobe Suite (Adobe Firefly).
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Many generative AI models are also available as open-source software, including Stable Diffusion and the LLaMA language model.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Smaller generative AI models with up to a few billion parameters can run on smartphones, embedded devices, and personal computers.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] For example, LLaMA-7B (a version with 7 billion parameters) can run on a Raspberry Pi 4 and one version of Stable Diffusion can run on an iPhone 11.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Larger models with tens of billions of parameters can run on laptop or desktop computers.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] To achieve an acceptable speed, models of this size may require accelerators such as the GPU chips produced by NVIDIA and AMD or the Neural Engine included in Apple silicon products.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] For example, the 65 billion parameter version of LLaMA can be configured to run on a desktop PC.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] The advantages of running generative AI locally include protection of privacy and intellectual property, and avoidance of rate limiting and censorship.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] The subreddit r/LocalLLaMA in particular focuses on using consumer-grade gaming graphics cards through such techniques as compression.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Language models with hundreds of billions of parameters, such as GPT-4 or PaLM, typically run on datacenter computers equipped with arrays of GPUs (such as NVIDIA's H100) or AI accelerator chips (such as Google's TPU).
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] These very large models are typically accessed as cloud services over the Internet.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2022, the United States New Export Controls on Advanced Computing and Semiconductors to China imposed restrictions on exports to China of GPU and AI accelerator chips used for generative AI.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Chips such as the NVIDIA A800 and the Biren Technology BR104 were developed to meet the requirements of the sanctions.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] There is free software on the market capable of recognizing text generated by generative artificial intelligence (such as GPTZero), as well as images, audio or video coming from it.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Potential mitigation strategies for detecting generative AI content include digital watermarking, content authentication, information retrieval, and machine learning classifier models.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Despite claims of accuracy, both free and paid AI text detectors have frequently produced false positives, mistakenly accusing students of submitting AI-generated work.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative adversarial networks (GANs) are a generative modeling technique which consist of two neural networks—the generator and the discriminator—trained simultaneously in a competitive setting.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] The generator creates synthetic data by transforming random noise into samples that resemble the training dataset.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] The discriminator is trained to distinguish the authentic data from synthetic data produced by the generator.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] The two models engage in a minimax game: the generator aims to create increasingly realistic data to "fool" the discriminator, while the discriminator improves its ability to distinguish real from fake data.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] This continuous training setup enables the generator to produce high-quality and realistic outputs.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Variational autoencoders (VAEs) are deep learning models that probabilistically encode data.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] They are typically used for tasks such as noise reduction from images, data compression, identifying unusual patterns, and facial recognition.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Unlike standard autoencoders, which compress input data into a fixed latent representation, VAEs model the latent space as a probability distribution, allowing for smooth sampling and interpolation between data points.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] The encoder ("recognition model") maps input data to a latent space, producing means and variances that define a probability distribution.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] The decoder ("generative model") samples from this latent distribution and attempts to reconstruct the original input.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Transformers became the foundation for the generative pre-trained transformer (GPT) series developed by OpenAI, replacing traditional recurrent and convolutional models.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] The self-attention mechanism enables the model to determine the relative importance of each token in a sequence when predicting the next token, thereby improving contextual understanding.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Unlike recurrent neural networks, transformers process tokens in parallel, which improves training efficiency and scalability.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] In the United States, a group of companies including OpenAI, Alphabet, and Meta signed a voluntary agreement with the Biden administration in July 2023 to watermark AI-generated content.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] In October 2023, Executive Order 14110 applied the Defense Production Act to require all US companies to report information to the federal government when training certain high-impact AI models.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] In the European Union (EU), the Artificial Intelligence Act includes requirements to disclose copyrighted material used to train generative AI systems, and to label any AI-generated output as such.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] In China, the Interim Measures for the Management of Generative AI Services introduced by the Cyberspace Administration of China regulates any public-facing generative AI.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] It includes requirements to watermark generated images or videos, regulations on training data and label quality, restrictions on personal data collection, and a guideline that generative AI services must "adhere to socialist core values".
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI systems such as ChatGPT and Midjourney are trained on large, publicly available datasets that include copyrighted works.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] AI developers have argued that such training is protected under fair use, while copyright holders have argued that it infringes their rights.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Proponents of fair use training have argued that it is a transformative use and does not involve making copies of copyrighted works available to the public.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Critics have argued that image generators such as Midjourney can create nearly-identical copies of some copyrighted images, and that generative AI programs compete with the content they are trained on.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] As of 2024, several lawsuits related to the use of copyrighted material in training are ongoing.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Getty Images has sued Stability AI over the use of its images to train Stable Diffusion.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Both the Authors Guild and The New York Times have sued Microsoft and OpenAI over the use of their works to train ChatGPT.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] A separate question is whether AI-generated works can qualify for copyright protection.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] The United States Copyright Office has ruled that works created by artificial intelligence without any human input cannot be copyrighted, because they lack human authorship.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Some legal professionals have suggested that *Naruto v.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] 9th Circuit Court of Appeals held that non-humans cannot be copyright holders of artistic works, could be a potential precedent in copyright litigation over works created by generative AI.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] However, the office has also begun taking public input to determine if these rules need to be refined for generative AI.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Whether such modifications rise to the minimum standard of originality required under Feist will depend on a case-by-case determination.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] In those cases where they do, the output should be copyrightable" Subsequently, the USCO registered the first visual artwork to be composed of entirely AI-generated materials, titled "A Single Piece of American Cheese".
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] The development of generative AI has raised concerns from governments, businesses, and individuals, resulting in protests, legal actions, calls to pause AI experiments, and actions by multiple governments.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] In addition, generative AI has a significant carbon footprint.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] A study presented in the 2026 Conference on Human Factors in Computing Systems found that overreliance on generative AI can decrease one's ability to discern misinformation, the study tracked participants, mostly from the UK and US, for a period of 4 weeks.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI can be used to generate and modify academic prose, paraphrase sources, and translate languages.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] The use of generative AI in a classroom setting has challenged traditional definitions of academic plagiarism, leading to a "cat-and-mouse" dynamic between students using AI and institutions attempting to detect it.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] In the immediate wake of ChatGPT's release, many school districts and universities issued temporary bans on the technology, though many institutions have since moved toward policies of managed integration.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] However, the implementation of these policies often lacks clarity.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Research suggests that the burden of interpreting "acceptable use" frequently falls on individual students and teachers, creating an environment where academic honesty becomes difficult to define and enforce.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] A commonly proposed use for teachers is grading and giving feedback.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Companies like Pearson and ETS use AI to score grammar, mechanics, usage, and style, but not for main ideas or overall structure.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] The National Council of Teachers of English stated that machine scoring makes students feel their writing is not worth reading.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] AI scoring has also given unfair results for students from different ethnic backgrounds.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] In April 2023, it was reported that image generation AI has resulted in 70% of the jobs for video game illustrators in China being lost.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] In July 2023, developments in generative AI contributed to the 2023 Hollywood labor disputes.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Fran Drescher, president of the Screen Actors Guild, declared that "artificial intelligence poses an existential threat to creative professions" during the 2023 SAG-AFTRA strike.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Voice generation AI has been seen as a potential challenge to the voice acting sector.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] However, a 2025 study concluded that the US labor market had so far not experienced a discernible disruption from generative AI.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Another study reported that Danish workers who used chatbots saved 2.8% of their time on average, and found no significant change in earnings or hours worked.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] In January 2023, *Futurism* broke the story that CNET had been using an undisclosed internal AI tool to write at least 77 of its stories; after the news broke, CNET posted corrections to 41 of the stories.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] In April 2023, *Die Aktuelle* published an AI-generated fake interview of Michael Schumacher.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] In May 2024, *Futurism* noted that a content management system video by AdVon Commerce, which had used generative AI to produce articles for many of the aforementioned outlets, appeared to show that they "had produced tens of thousands of articles for more than 150 publishers".
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2025, a report from the American Sunlight Project stated that Pravda network was publishing as many as 10,000 articles a day, and concluded that much of this content aimed to push Russian narratives into large language models through their training data.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] In June 2024, Reuters Institute published its *Digital News Report for 2024*.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] In a survey of people in America and Europe, Reuters Institute reports that 52% and 47% respectively are uncomfortable with news produced by "mostly AI with some human oversight", and 23% and 15% respectively report being comfortable.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] 42% of Americans and 33% of Europeans reported that they were comfortable with news produced by "mainly human with some help from AI".
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] The results of global surveys reported that people were more uncomfortable with news topics including politics (46%), crime (43%), and local news (37%) produced by AI than other news topics.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] A 2025 Pew Research Survey found roughly half of all U.S. adults say that AI will have a very (24%) or somewhat (26%) negative impact on the news people get in the U.S. over the next 20 years.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] A language model may associate certain professions with specific genders if such patterns are prevalent in the data.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Similarly, image generation systems prompted with terms such as "a photo of a CEO" have been observed to disproportionately generate images of white male individuals when trained on biased datasets.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] AI software, when using voice recognition software in particular, struggles to recognize and understand speech impediments.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] For example, people with a stutter struggle to activate voice-activated assistants such as Gemini and Siri due to how the software was trained.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Companies that use AI systems to hire for new positions also filter out people with accents and speech due to voice recognition software incorrectly transcribing how candidates speak during the interview process.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Because of this, people with disabilities and uncommon accents don't often make it to a human interviewer when these generative AI systems are used.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] This is due to many AI models being trained and produced in the United States, and therefore, off of American accents.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Deepfakes (a portmanteau of "deep learning" and "fake") are AI-generated media that take a person in an existing image or video and replace them with someone else's likeness using artificial neural networks.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Deepfakes have garnered widespread attention and concerns for their uses in deepfake celebrity pornographic videos, revenge porn, fake news, hoaxes, health disinformation, financial fraud, and covert foreign election interference.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Instances of users abusing software to generate controversial statements in the vocal style of celebrities, public officials, and other famous individuals have raised ethical concerns over voice generation AI.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] In response, companies such as ElevenLabs have stated that they would work on mitigating potential abuse through safeguards and identity verification.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Concerns and fandoms have spawned from AI-generated music.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] The same software used to clone voices has been used on famous musicians' voices to create songs that mimic their voices, gaining both tremendous popularity and criticism.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Similar techniques have also been used to create improved quality or full-length versions of songs that have been leaked or have yet to be released.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI has been noted for its use by state-sponsored propaganda campaigns in information laundering.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] According to a 2025 report by Graphika, generative AI is used to launder articles from Chinese state media such as China Global Television Network through various social media sites in an attempt to disguise the articles' origin.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] A paper published by researchers at Amazon Web Services AI Labs found that over 57% of sentences from a sample of over 6 billion sentences from Common Crawl, a snapshot of web pages, were machine translated.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Many of these automated translations were seen as lower quality, especially for sentences that were translated into at least three languages.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Wolof, Xhosa) were translated across more languages than higher-resource languages (ex.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] The adoption of generative AI tools led to an explosion of AI-generated content across multiple domains.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] A study from University College London estimated that in 2023, more than 60,000 scholarly articles—over 1% of all publications—were likely written with LLM assistance.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] According to Stanford University's Institute for Human-Centered AI, approximately 17.5% of newly published computer science papers and 16.9% of peer review text now incorporate content generated by LLMs.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] If AI-generated content is included in new data crawls from the Internet for additional training of AI models, defects in the resulting models may occur.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Training an AI model exclusively on the output of another AI model produces a lower-quality model.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Repeating this process, where each new model is trained on the previous model's output, leads to progressive degradation and eventually results in a "model collapse" after multiple iterations.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] On the other side, synthetic data can be deployed to train machine learning models while preserving user privacy.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] The approach is not limited to text generation; image generation has been employed to train computer vision models.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Many websites that allow explicit AI generated images or videos have been created, and this has been used to create illegal content, such as rape, child sexual abuse material, necrophilia, and zoophilia.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI's ability to create realistic fake content has been exploited in numerous types of cybercrime, including phishing scams.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Deepfake video and audio have been used to create disinformation and fraud.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2020, former Google click fraud czar Shuman Ghosemajumder argued that once deepfake videos become perfectly realistic, they would stop appearing remarkable to viewers, potentially leading to uncritical acceptance of false information.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Additionally, large language models and other forms of text-generation AI have been used to create fake reviews of e-commerce websites to boost ratings.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Cybercriminals have created large language models focused on fraud, including WormGPT and FraudGPT.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] A 2023 study showed that generative AI can be vulnerable to jailbreaks, reverse psychology and prompt injection attacks, enabling attackers to obtain help with harmful requests, such as for crafting social engineering and phishing attacks.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Additionally, other researchers have demonstrated that open-source models can be fine-tuned to remove their safety restrictions at low cost.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2025, Israel signed a $6 million contract with the US-based firm Clock Tower X that aimed to influence ChatGPT, Gemini and Grok by spreading pro-Israel information onto social media and websites.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] This was in an attempt to take advantage of the retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) technique which is used by LLMs to provide more up-to-date information.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] The CLOUD Act allows United States authorities to request data from covered service providers, including some AI service providers, regardless of where the data is physically stored.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Courts can require parent companies to provide data held by their subsidiaries, and such orders may be accompanied by nondisclosure requirements preventing the provider from notifying affected users.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] This framework has been described in legal commentary as creating legal tension with Article 48 of the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which restricts the transfer of personal data in response to foreign court or administrative orders unless based on an international agreement.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] As a result, service providers operating in both jurisdictions may face competing legal obligations under U.S. and EU law.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] AI has a significant carbon footprint due to growing energy consumption from both training and usage.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] There is also concern that these impacts may increase as these models are incorporated into widely used search engines such as Google Search and Bing, as chatbots and other applications become more popular, and as models need to be retrained.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Training frontier AI models requires an enormous amount of computing power.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Usually only Big Tech companies have the financial resources to make such investments.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Smaller start-ups such as Cohere and OpenAI end up buying access to data centers from Google and Microsoft respectively.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Tools such as GPTZero can detect content generated by AI.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] However, they can also make false accusations (false positives).
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] Digital watermarking is a technique that improves detection accuracy.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] It works by altering the generated content at the source, in subtle ways which can be detected by corresponding software.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2023, OpenAI developed a watermarking tool for ChatGPT.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] They didn't release it, because they worried that users would switch to competitors.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] They also argued that it would be easy to circumvent, for example by asking another AI to rephrase.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] In March 2025, the Cyberspace Administration of China issued rules, requiring online service providers to label AI content.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] In May 2025, Google deployed its watermarking tool, SynthID.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] It marks output from Gemini (text), Imagen (images), and Veo (video).
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] To detect output from these products, one uses Google's "SynthID detector" portal.
[src:music-generation-ai/generative-artificial-intelligence] In June 2025, users mistakenly accused gaming companies of using generative AI for the video games *Little Droid* and *Catly*.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Music software utilizes artificial intelligence to generate, classify, or recommend music.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Similar to its applications in other fields, AI in music simulates complex human cognitive processes.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] A prominent feature is the capability of an AI algorithm to learn from historical data, such as in computer accompaniment technology, where the AI listens to a human performer and accompanies them in real-time.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Artificial intelligence also drives interactive composition technologies that respond dynamically to live performances.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Modern applications expand across the entire industry lifecycle, transforming music composition, production, and performance, as well as how music is marketed and consumed.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Furthermore, conversational agents leverage voice recognition and natural language processing to enable voice-controlled music playback, bridging current research in music theory with advanced digital sound processing.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] In the 1950s and the 1960s, music made by artificial intelligence was not fully original, but generated from templates that people had already defined and given to the AI, with this being known as rule-based systems.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] As time passed, computers became more powerful, which allowed machine learning and artificial neural networks to help in the music industry by giving AI large amounts of data.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] By the early 2000s, more advancements in artificial intelligence had been made, with generative adversarial networks (GANs) and deep learning being used to help AI compose more original music that is more complex and varied than possible before.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Notable AI-driven projects, such as OpenAI's MuseNet and Google's Magenta, have demonstrated AI's ability to generate compositions that mimic various musical styles.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] 20th century art historian Erwin Panofsky proposed that in all art, there existed three levels of meaning: primary meaning, or the natural subject; secondary meaning, or the conventional subject; and tertiary meaning, the intrinsic content of the subject.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] AI music explores the foremost of these, creating music without the "intention" that is usually behind it, leaving composers who listen to machine-generated pieces feeling unsettled by the lack of apparent meaning.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Artificial intelligence finds its beginnings in music with the transcription problem: accurately recording a performance into musical notation as it is played.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Père Engramelle's schematic of a "piano roll", a mode of automatically recording note timing and duration in a way which could be easily transcribed to proper musical notation by hand, was first implemented by German engineers J.F.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] In 1957, the ILLIAC I (Illinois Automatic Computer) produced the "Illiac Suite for String Quartet", a completely computer-generated piece of music.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] The computer was programmed to accomplish this by composer Leonard Isaacson and mathematician Lejaren Hiller.In 1960, Russian researcher Rudolf Zaripov published the first worldwide paper on algorithmic music composition using the Ural-1 computer.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] In 1965, inventor Ray Kurzweil developed software capable of recognizing musical patterns and synthesizing new compositions from them.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] The computer first appeared on the quiz show *I've Got a Secret* that same year.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] By 1983, Yamaha Corporation's Kansei Music System had gained momentum, and a paper was published on its development in 1989.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] In 1997, an artificial intelligence program named Experiments in Musical Intelligence (EMI) appeared to outperform a human composer at the task of composing a piece of music to imitate the style of Bach.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] EMI would later become the basis for a more sophisticated algorithm called Emily Howell, named for its creator.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] In 2002, the music research team at the Sony Computer Science Laboratory in Paris, led by French composer and scientist François Pachet, designed the Continuator, an algorithm uniquely capable of resuming a composition after a live musician stopped.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Emily Howell would continue to make advancements in musical artificial intelligence, publishing her first album *From Darkness, Light* in 2009.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Since then, many more pieces by artificial intelligence and various groups have been published.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] In 2010, Iamus became the first AI to produce a fragment of original contemporary classical music, in its own style: "Iamus' Opus 1".
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Located at the Universidad de Malága (Malága University) in Spain, the computer can generate a fully original piece in a variety of musical styles.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] In August 2019, a large dataset consisting of 12,197 MIDI songs, each with their lyrics and melodies, was created to investigate the feasibility of neural melody generation from lyrics using a deep conditional LSTM-GAN method.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] With progress in generative AI, models capable of creating complete musical compositions (including lyrics) from a simple text description have begun to emerge.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Two notable web applications in this field are Suno AI, launched in December 2023, and Udio, which followed in April 2024.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] In November 2025 the AI generated song "Walk My Walk" presented as being by Breaking Rust topped the Billboard Country Digital Song Sales chart.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] The same year, AI band The Velvet Sundown attracted one million listeners on Spotify.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Streaming service Deezer started tagging AI generated songs and excluding them from its editorialized playlists.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Their tool builds on former published research work on the nature of AI music's artefacts.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] In November 2025, the service claimed that 50,000 AI generated songs were uploaded daily, about a third of total uploads.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Composers and artists like Jennifer Walshe and Holly Herndon have been exploring aspects of music AI for years in their performances and musical works.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Another original approach of humans "imitating AI" can be found in the 43-hour sound installation *String Quartet(s)* by Georges Lentz.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Developed at Princeton University by Ge Wang and Perry Cook, ChucK is a text-based, cross-platform language.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] By extracting and classifying the theoretical techniques it finds in musical pieces, the software is able to synthesize entirely new pieces from the techniques it has learned.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] The technology is used by SLOrk (Stanford Laptop Orchestra) and PLOrk (Princeton Laptop Orchestra).
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Jukedeck was a website that let people use artificial intelligence to generate original, royalty-free music for use in videos.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] The team started building the music generation technology in 2010, formed a company around it in 2012, and launched the website publicly in 2015.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] The technology used was originally a rule-based algorithmic composition system, which was later replaced with artificial neural networks.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] The website was used to create over 1 million pieces of music, and brands that used it included Coca-Cola, Google, UKTV, and the Natural History Museum, London.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] In 2019, the company was acquired by ByteDance.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] MorpheuS is a research project by Dorien Herremans and Elaine Chew at Queen Mary University of London, funded by a Marie Skłodowská-Curie EU project.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] The system uses an optimization approach based on a variable neighborhood search algorithm to morph existing template pieces into novel pieces with a set level of tonal tension that changes dynamically throughout the piece.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] This optimization approach allows for the integration of a pattern detection technique in order to enforce long term structure and recurring themes in the generated music.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Pieces composed by MorpheuS have been performed at concerts in both Stanford and London.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Created in February 2016, in Luxembourg, AIVA is a program that produces soundtracks for any type of media.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] The algorithms behind AIVA are based on deep learning architectures AIVA has also been used to compose a Rock track called *On the Edge*, as well as a pop tune *Love Sick* in collaboration with singer Taryn Southern, for the creation of her 2018 album "I am AI".
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Google's Magenta team has published several AI music applications and technical papers since their launch in 2016.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] In 2017 they released the NSynth algorithm and dataset, and an open source hardware musical instrument, designed to facilitate musicians in using the algorithm.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] The instrument was used by notable artists such as Grimes and YACHT in their albums.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] In 2018, they released a piano improvisation app called Piano Genie.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] This was later followed by Magenta Studio, a suite of 5 MIDI plugins that allow music producers to elaborate on existing music in their DAW.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] In 2023, their machine learning team published a technical paper on GitHub that described MusicLM, a private text-to-music generator which they'd developed.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Riffusion is a neural network, designed by Seth Forsgren and Hayk Martiros, that generates music using images of sound rather than audio.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] The resulting music has been described as "*de otro mundo*" (otherworldly), although unlikely to replace man-made music.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] The model was made available on December 15, 2022, with the code also freely available on GitHub.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] While these files were only several seconds long, the model could also use latent space between outputs to interpolate different files together (using the img2img capabilities of SD).
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] It was one of many models derived from Stable Diffusion.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] In December 2022, Mubert similarly used Stable Diffusion to turn descriptive text into music loops.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] In January 2023, Google published a paper on their own text-to-music generator called MusicLM.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Forsgren and Martiros formed a startup, also called Riffusion, and raised $4 million in venture capital funding in October 2023.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Spike AI is an AI-based audio plug-in, developed by Spike Stent in collaboration with his son Joshua Stent and friend Henry Ramsey, that analyzes tracks and provides suggestions to increase clarity and other aspects during mixing.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Communication is done by using a chatbot trained on Spike Stent's personal data.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] The plug-in integrates into digital audio workstation.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Artificial intelligence can potentially impact how producers create music by giving reiterations of a track that follow a prompt given by the creator.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] These prompts allow the AI to follow a certain style that the artist is trying to go for.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] AI has also been seen in musical analysis where it has been used for feature extraction, pattern recognition, and musical recommendations.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] New tools that are powered by artificial intelligence have been made to help aid in generating original music compositions, like AIVA (Artificial Intelligence Virtual Artist) and Udio.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] This is done by giving an AI model data of already-existing music and having it analyze the data using deep learning techniques to generate music in many different genres, such as classical music or electronic music.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Musical and choral classrooms are already implementing AI driven programs to aid in musical learning, and development of creative skills in students where AI has shown to provide a statistically significant increase.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Several musicians such as Dua Lipa, Elton John, Nick Cave, Paul McCartney and Sting have criticized the use of AI in music and are encouraging the UK government to act on this matter.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Another example of this protest is the silent 2025 album *Is This What We Want?*.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Some artists have encouraged the use of AI in music such as Grimes.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] While helpful in generating new music, many issues have come up since artificial intelligence has begun making music.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Some major concerns include how the economy will be impacted with AI taking over music production, who truly owns music generated by AI, and a lower demand for human-made musical compositions.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Some critics argue that AI diminishes the value of human creativity, while proponents see it as an augmentative tool that expands artistic possibilities rather than replacing human musicians.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Additionally, concerns have been raised about AI's potential to homogenize music.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] AI-driven models often generate compositions based on existing trends, which some fear could limit musical diversity.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Addressing this concern, researchers are working on AI systems that incorporate more nuanced creative elements, allowing for greater stylistic variation.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Another major concern about artificial intelligence in music is copyright laws.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] In the United States, the current legal framework tends to apply traditional copyright laws to AI, despite its differences with the human creative process.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] However, music outputs solely generated by AI are not granted copyright protection.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] One instance of this was seen when SACEM, a professional organization of songwriters, composers, and music publishers demanded that PozaLabs, an AI music generation startup refrain from utilizing any music affiliated with them for training models.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] The situation in the European Union (EU) is similar to the US, because its legal framework also emphasizes the role of human involvement in a copyright-protected work.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] The reCreating Europe project, funded by the European Union's Horizon 2020 research and innovation program, delves into the challenges posed by AI-generated contents including music, suggesting legal certainty and balanced protection that encourages innovation while respecting copyright norms.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] The recognition of AIVA marks a significant departure from traditional views on authorship and copyrights in the realm of music composition, allowing AI artists capable of releasing music and earning royalties.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] This acceptance marks AIVA as a pioneering instance where an AI has been formally acknowledged within the music production.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] The recent advancements in artificial intelligence made by groups such as Stability AI, OpenAI, and Google has incurred an enormous sum of copyright claims leveled against generative technology, including AI music.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Should these lawsuits succeed, the machine learning models behind these technologies would have their datasets restricted to the public domain.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Strides towards addressing ethical issues have been made as well, such as the collaboration between Sound Ethics(a company promoting ethical AI usage in the music industry) and UC Irvine, focusing on ethical frameworks and the responsible usage of AI.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Internationally, systemic resistance against unauthorized generative models has escalated; in mid-2026, major entertainment coalitions in South Korea formed a unified front against artificial intelligence copyright infringement.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Market infrastructure analysts noted that this cross-border consolidation marks a critical shift toward protecting sovereign cultural assets, serving as a legislative blueprint for global intellectual property frameworks fighting against automated sonic commodification.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] A more nascent development of AI in music is the application of audio deepfakes to cast the lyrics or musical style of a pre-existing song to the voice or style of another artist.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] This has raised many concerns regarding the legality of technology, as well as the ethics of employing it, particularly in the context of artistic identity.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Furthermore, it has also raised the question of to whom the authorship of these works is attributed.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] As AI cannot hold authorship of its own, current speculation suggests that there will be no clear answer until further rulings are made regarding machine learning technologies as a whole.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Most recently, preventative measures have started to be developed by Google and Universal Music group who have taken in royalties and credited attribution in order to allow producers to replicate the voices and styles of artists.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] The track was submitted for Grammy consideration for the best rap song and song of the year.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] It went viral and gained traction on TikTok and received a positive response from the audience, leading to its official release on Apple Music, Spotify, and YouTube in April 2023.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Many believed the track was fully composed by an AI software, but the producer claimed the songwriting, production, and original vocals (pre-conversion) were still done by him.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] It would later be rescinded from any Grammy considerations due to it not following the guidelines necessary to be considered for a Grammy award.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] The track would end up being removed from all music platforms by Universal Music Group.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] The song was a watershed moment for AI voice cloning, and models have since been created for hundreds, if not thousands, of popular singers and rappers.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] In 2013, country music singer Randy Travis suffered a stroke which left him unable to sing.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] In the meantime, vocalist James Dupré toured on his behalf, singing his songs for him.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Travis and longtime producer Kyle Lehning released a new song in May 2024 titled "Where That Came From", Travis's first new song since his stroke.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] The recording uses AI technology to re-create Travis's singing voice, having been composited from over 40 existing vocal recordings alongside those of Dupré.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Since 2024, rapper Kanye West has been using artificial intelligence deepfakes of his own voice.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] His usage of deepfakes started during the production of his album *Vultures 2*, where the songs "Field Trip" and "Sky City" drew suspicion of artificial intelligence usage; further updates to the songs "Forever" and "530" would also be accused of using AI.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Artist Ty Dolla Sign, who released *Vultures 2* with West, would confirm the allegations in 2025 during an interview.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] West would subsequently confirm that his subsequent solo album, *Bully*, also used artificial intelligence.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Though West would confirm in 2026 that he would remove the AI, the physical versions of the album would still contain AI.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] His unreleased album *Cuck* and the 2025 re-release of *Donda 2* would also draw accusations of AI usage.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Playboi Carti has also been accused of using artificial intelligence deepfakes.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] The allegations followed the release of the song "Timeless", a collaboration with The Weeknd, where his verse was accused of using artificial intelligence.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] The allegations would further intensify after the release of his album *Music*, where "Rather Lie" and "Fine Shit" were also accused of using artificial intelligence.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Playboi Carti would deny the accusations.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Numerous OPM music have had notable AI covers.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] An AI cover of "Pahina" by Cup of Joe hit the Spotify Philippines' Viral Songs chart, with a negative reaction from one of the band members, and has since been removed from Spotify.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Lofi Town, an AI artist covering Filipino songs, also hit Spotify Philippines' Top Artists list, with negative reactions from several OPM artists, including Maki, Adie, mrld, TJ Monterde, Janine Teñoso, and Angela Ken.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] An AI cover of "Kay Tagal Kitang Hinintay" was also criticized by Karylle.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Artificial intelligence music encompasses a number of technical approaches used for music composition, analysis, classification, and suggestion.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Techniques used are drawn from deep learning, machine learning, natural language processing, and signal processing.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Current systems are able to compose entire musical compositions, parse affective content, accompany human players in real-time, and acquire patterns of user and context-dependent preferences.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Symbolic music generation is the generation of music in discrete symbolic forms such as MIDI, where note and timing are precisely defined.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Early systems employed rule-based systems and Markov models, but modern systems employ deep learning to a large extent.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Recurrent Neural Networks (RNNs), and more precisely Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) networks, have been employed in modeling temporal dependencies of musical sequences.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] They may be used to generate melodies, harmonies, and counterpoints in various musical genres.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Transformer models such as Music Transformer and MuseNet became more popular for symbolic generation due to their ability to model long-range dependencies and scalability.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] These models were employed to generate multi-instrument polyphonic music and stylistic imitations.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] This method generates music as raw audio waveforms instead of symbolic notation.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] DeepMind's WaveNet is an early example that uses autoregressive sampling to generate high-fidelity audio.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Generative Adversarial Networks (GANs) and Variational Autoencoders (VAEs) are being used more and more in new audio texture synthesis and timbre combination of different instruments.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] NSynth (Neural Synthesizer), a Google Magenta project, uses a WaveNet-like autoencoder to learn latent audio representations and thereby generate completely novel instrumental sounds.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Music Information Retrieval (MIR) is the extraction of musically relevant information from audio recordings to be utilized in applications such as genre classification, instrument recognition, mood recognition, beat detection, and similarity estimation.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] CNNs on spectrogram features have been very accurate on these tasks.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] SVMs and k-Nearest Neighbors (k-NN) are also used for classification on features such as Mel-frequency cepstral coefficients (MFCCs).
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Hybrid systems combine symbolic and sound-based methods to draw on their respective strengths.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] They can compose high-level symbolic compositions and synthesize them as natural sound.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Interactive systems in real-time allow for AI to instantaneously respond to human input to support live performance.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Reinforcement learning and rule-based agents tend to be utilized to allow for human–AI co-creation in improvisation contexts.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Affective computing techniques enable AI systems to classify or create music based on some affective content.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] The models use musical features such as tempo, mode, and timbre to classify or influence listener emotions.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Deep learning models have been trained for classifying music based on affective content and even creating music intended to have affective impacts.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Music recommenders employ AI to suggest tracks to users based on what they have heard, their tastes, and information available in context.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Collaborative filtering, content-based filtering, and hybrid filtering are most widely applied, deep learning being utilized for fine-tuning.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Graph-based and matrix factorization methods are used within commercial systems like Spotify and YouTube Music to represent complex user-item relationships.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] AI is also used in audio engineering automation such as mixing and mastering.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Such systems level, equalize, pan, and compress to give well-balanced sound outputs.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Software such as LANDR and iZotope Ozone utilize machine learning in emulating professional audio engineers' decisions.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Natural language generation also applies to songwriting assistance and lyrics generation.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Transformer language models like GPT-3 have also been proven to be able to generate stylistic and coherent lyrics from input prompts, themes, or feeling.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] There even exist AI programs that assist with rhyme scheme, syllable count, and poem form.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Recent developments include multimodal AI systems that integrate music with other media, e.g., dance, video, and text.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] These can generate background scores in synchronization with video sequences or generate dance choreography from audio input.
[src:music-generation-ai/music-and-artificial-intelligence] Cross-modal retrieval systems allow one to search for music using images, text, or gestures.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] In artificial neural networks, **recurrent neural networks** (**RNNs**) are designed for processing sequential data, such as text, speech, and time series, where the order of elements is important.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Unlike feedforward neural networks, which process inputs independently, RNNs utilize recurrent connections, where the output of a neuron at one time step is fed back as input to the network at the next time step.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] This enables RNNs to capture temporal dependencies and patterns within sequences.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] The fundamental building block of RNN is the *recurrent unit*, which maintains a *hidden state*—a form of memory that is updated at each time step based on the current input and the previous hidden state.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] This feedback mechanism allows the network to learn from past inputs and incorporate that knowledge into its current processing.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] RNNs have been successfully applied to tasks such as unsegmented, connected handwriting recognition, speech recognition, natural language processing, and neural machine translation.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] However, traditional RNNs suffer from the vanishing gradient problem, which limits their ability to learn long-range dependencies.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] This issue was addressed by the development of the long short-term memory (LSTM) architecture in 1997, making it the standard RNN variant for handling long-term dependencies.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Later, gated recurrent units (GRUs) were introduced as a more computationally efficient alternative.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Nevertheless, RNNs remain relevant for applications where computational efficiency, real-time processing, or the inherent sequential nature of data is crucial.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] The word "recurrent" is used to describe loop-like structures in anatomy.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] In 1901, Cajal observed "recurrent semicircles" in the cerebellar cortex formed by parallel fiber, Purkinje cells, and granule cells.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] In 1933, Lorente de Nó discovered "recurrent, reciprocal connections" by Golgi's method, and proposed that excitatory loops explain certain aspects of the vestibulo-ocular reflex.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] During 1940s, multiple people proposed the existence of feedback in the brain, which was a contrast to the previous understanding of the neural system as a purely feedforward structure.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Hebb considered "reverberating circuit" as an explanation for short-term memory.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] The McCulloch and Pitts paper (1943), which proposed the McCulloch-Pitts neuron model, considered networks that contains cycles.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] The current activity of such networks can be affected by activity indefinitely far in the past.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] They were both interested in closed loops as possible explanations for e.g. epilepsy and causalgia.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Recurrent inhibition was proposed in 1946 as a negative feedback mechanism in motor control.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Neural feedback loops were a common topic of discussion at the Macy conferences.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] See for an extensive review of recurrent neural network models in neuroscience.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Frank Rosenblatt in 1960 published "close-loop cross-coupled perceptrons", which are 3-layered perceptron networks whose middle layer contains recurrent connections that change by a Hebbian learning rule.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Similar networks were published by Kaoru Nakano in 1971, Shun'ichi Amari in 1972, and William A.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Little in 1974, who was acknowledged by Hopfield in his 1982 paper.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Another origin of RNN was statistical mechanics.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] The Ising model was developed by Wilhelm Lenz and Ernst Ising in the 1920s as a simple statistical mechanical model of magnets at equilibrium.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Glauber in 1963 studied the Ising model evolving in time, as a process towards equilibrium (Glauber dynamics), adding in the component of time.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] The Sherrington–Kirkpatrick model of spin glass, published in 1975, is the Hopfield network with random initialization.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Sherrington and Kirkpatrick found that it is highly likely for the energy function of the SK model to have many local minima.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] In the 1982 paper, Hopfield applied this recently developed theory to study the Hopfield network with binary activation functions.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] In a 1984 paper he extended this to continuous activation functions.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] It became a standard model for the study of neural networks through statistical mechanics.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Modern RNN networks are mainly based on two architectures: LSTM and BRNN.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] At the resurgence of neural networks in the 1980s, recurrent networks were studied again.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] They were sometimes called "iterated nets".
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Two early influential works were the Jordan network (1986) and the Elman network (1990), which applied RNN to study cognitive psychology.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] In 1993, a neural history compressor system solved a "Very Deep Learning" task that required more than 1000 subsequent layers in an RNN unfolded in time.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Long short-term memory (LSTM) networks were invented by Hochreiter and Schmidhuber in 1995 and set accuracy records in multiple applications domains.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] It became the default choice for RNN architecture.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Bidirectional recurrent neural networks (BRNN) use two RNNs that process the same input in opposite directions.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] These two are often combined, giving the bidirectional LSTM architecture.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Around 2006, bidirectional LSTM started to revolutionize speech recognition, outperforming traditional models in certain speech applications.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] They also improved large-vocabulary speech recognition and text-to-speech synthesis and was used in Google voice search, and dictation on Android devices.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] They broke records for improved machine translation, language modeling and Multilingual Language Processing.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Also, LSTM combined with convolutional neural networks (CNNs) improved automatic image captioning.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] The idea of encoder-decoder sequence transduction had been developed in the early 2010s.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] The papers most commonly cited as the originators that produced seq2seq are two papers from 2014.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] A seq2seq architecture employs two RNN, typically LSTM, an "encoder" and a "decoder", for sequence transduction, such as machine translation.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] They became state of the art in machine translation, and were instrumental in the development of attention mechanisms and transformers.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] An RNN-based model can be factored into two parts: configuration and architecture.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Multiple RNNs can be combined in a data flow, and the data flow itself is the configuration.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Each RNN itself may have any architecture, including LSTM, GRU, etc.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] In words, it is a neural network that maps an input $x_{t}$ into an output $y_{t}$ , with the hidden vector $h_{t}$ playing the role of "memory", a partial record of all previous input-output pairs.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] At each step, it transforms input to an output, and modifies its "memory" to help it to better perform future processing.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] The illustration to the right may be misleading to many because practical neural network topologies are frequently organized in "layers" and the drawing gives that appearance.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] However, what appears to be layers are, in fact, different steps in time, "unfolded" to produce the appearance of layers.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] A **stacked RNN**, or **deep RNN**, is composed of multiple RNNs stacked one above the other.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Each layer operates as a stand-alone RNN, and each layer's output sequence is used as the input sequence to the layer above.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] There is no conceptual limit to the depth of stacked RNN.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] A **bidirectional RNN** (biRNN) is composed of two RNNs, one processing the input sequence in one direction, and another in the opposite direction.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Bidirectional RNN allows the model to process a token both in the context of what came before it and what came after it.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] By stacking multiple bidirectional RNNs together, the model can process a token increasingly contextually.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] The ELMo model (2018) is a stacked bidirectional LSTM which takes character-level as inputs and produces word-level embeddings.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Two RNNs can be run front-to-back in an **encoder-decoder** configuration.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] The encoder RNN processes an input sequence into a sequence of hidden vectors, and the decoder RNN processes the sequence of hidden vectors to an output sequence, with an optional attention mechanism.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] This was used to construct state of the art neural machine translators during the 2014–2017 period.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] This was an instrumental step towards the development of transformers.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] An RNN may process data with more than one dimension.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] PixelRNN processes two-dimensional data, with many possible directions.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] For example, the row-by-row direction processes an $n\times n$ grid of vectors $x_{i,j}$ in the following order: $x_{1,1},x_{1,2},\dots ,x_{1,n},x_{2,1},x_{2,2},\dots ,x_{2,n},\dots ,x_{n,n}$ The **diagonal BiLSTM** uses two LSTMs to process the same grid.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] One processes it from the top-left corner to the bottom-right, such that it processes $x_{i,j}$ depending on its hidden state and cell state on the top and the left side: $h_{i-1,j},c_{i-1,j}$ and $h_{i,j-1},c_{i,j-1}$ .
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] The other processes it from the top-right corner to the bottom-left.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] The **Hopfield network** is an RNN in which all connections across layers are equally sized.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] It requires stationary inputs and is thus not a general RNN, as it does not process sequences of patterns.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] However, it guarantees that it will converge.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] If the connections are trained using Hebbian learning, then the Hopfield network can perform as robust content-addressable memory, resistant to connection alteration.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] An **Elman network** is a three-layer network (arranged horizontally as *x*, *y*, and *z* in the illustration) with the addition of a set of context units (*u* in the illustration).
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] The middle (hidden) layer is connected to these context units fixed with a weight of one.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] At each time step, the input is fed forward and a learning rule is applied.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] The fixed back-connections save a copy of the previous values of the hidden units in the context units (since they propagate over the connections before the learning rule is applied).
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Thus the network can maintain a sort of state, allowing it to perform tasks such as sequence-prediction that are beyond the power of a standard multilayer perceptron.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Elman and Jordan networks are also known as "Simple recurrent networks" (SRN).
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Many applications use stacks of LSTMs, for which it is called "deep LSTM".
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] LSTM can learn to recognize context-sensitive languages unlike previous models based on hidden Markov models (HMM) and similar concepts.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Their performance on polyphonic music modeling and speech signal modeling was found to be similar to that of long short-term memory.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] There does not appear to be particular performance difference between LSTM and GRU.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Introduced by Bart Kosko, a bidirectional associative memory (BAM) network is a variant of a Hopfield network that stores associative data as a vector.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] The bidirectionality comes from passing information through a matrix and its transpose.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Typically, bipolar encoding is preferred to binary encoding of the associative pairs.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Recently, stochastic BAM models using Markov stepping are optimized for increased network stability and relevance to real-world applications.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] A BAM network has two layers, either of which can be driven as an input to recall an association and produce an output on the other layer.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] A **recursive neural network** is created by applying the same set of weights recursively over a differentiable graph-like structure by traversing the structure in topological order.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Such networks are typically also trained by the reverse mode of automatic differentiation.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] They can process distributed representations of structure, such as logical terms.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] A special case of recursive neural networks is the RNN whose structure corresponds to a linear chain.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Recursive neural networks have been applied to natural language processing.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] The *recursive neural tensor network* uses a tensor-based composition function for all nodes in the tree.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Recurrent neural networks are Turing complete and can run arbitrary programs to process arbitrary sequences of inputs.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] An RNN can be trained into a conditionally generative model of sequences, aka **autoregression**.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Concretely, let us consider the problem of machine translation, that is, given a sequence $(x_{1},x_{2},\dots ,x_{n})$ of English words, the model is to produce a sequence $(y_{1},\dots ,y_{m})$ of French words.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Now, during training, the encoder half of the model would first ingest $(x_{1},x_{2},\dots ,x_{n})$ , then the decoder half would start generating a sequence $({\hat {y}}_{1},{\hat {y}}_{2},\dots ,{\hat {y}}_{l})$ .
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] The problem is that if the model makes a mistake early on, say at ${\hat {y}}_{2}$ , then subsequent tokens are likely to also be mistakes.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] This makes it inefficient for the model to obtain a learning signal, since the model would mostly learn to shift ${\hat {y}}_{2}$ towards $y_{2}$ , but not the others.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Gradient descent is a first-order iterative optimization algorithm for finding the minimum of a function.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] In neural networks, it can be used to minimize the error term by changing each weight in proportion to the derivative of the error with respect to that weight, provided the non-linear activation functions are differentiable.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] The standard method for training RNN by gradient descent is the "backpropagation through time" (BPTT) algorithm, which is a special case of the general algorithm of backpropagation.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] A more computationally expensive online variant is called "Real-Time Recurrent Learning" or RTRL, which is an instance of automatic differentiation in the forward accumulation mode with stacked tangent vectors.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Unlike BPTT, this algorithm is local in time but not local in space.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] In this context, local in space means that a unit's weight vector can be updated using only information stored in the connected units and the unit itself such that update complexity of a single unit is linear in the dimensionality of the weight vector.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Local in time means that the updates take place continually (on-line) and depend only on the most recent time step rather than on multiple time steps within a given time horizon as in BPTT.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Biological neural networks appear to be local with respect to both time and space.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] An online hybrid between BPTT and RTRL with intermediate complexity exists, along with variants for continuous time.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] A major problem with gradient descent for standard RNN architectures is that error gradients vanish exponentially quickly with the size of the time lag between important events.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] LSTM combined with a BPTT/RTRL hybrid learning method attempts to overcome these problems.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] This problem is also solved in the independently recurrent neural network (IndRNN) by reducing the context of a neuron to its own past state and the cross-neuron information can then be explored in the following layers.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Memories of different ranges including long-term memory can be learned without the gradient vanishing and exploding problems.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] The online algorithm called **causal recursive backpropagation** (CRBP), implements and combines BPTT and RTRL paradigms for locally recurrent networks.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] It works with the most general locally recurrent networks.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] The CRBP algorithm can minimize the global error term.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] This fact improves the stability of the algorithm, providing a unifying view of gradient calculation techniques for recurrent networks with local feedback.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] One approach to gradient information computation in RNNs with arbitrary architectures is based on signal-flow graphs diagrammatic derivation.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] It uses the BPTT batch algorithm, based on Lee's theorem for network sensitivity calculations.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] It was proposed by Wan and Beaufays, while its fast online version was proposed by Campolucci, Uncini and Piazza.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] The connectionist temporal classification (CTC) is a specialized loss function for training RNNs for sequence modeling problems where the timing is variable.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Training the weights in a neural network can be modeled as a non-linear global optimization problem.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] A target function can be formed to evaluate the fitness or error of a particular weight vector as follows: First, the weights in the network are set according to the weight vector.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Next, the network is evaluated against the training sequence.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Typically, the sum-squared difference between the predictions and the target values specified in the training sequence is used to represent the error of the current weight vector.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Arbitrary global optimization techniques may then be used to minimize this target function.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] The most common global optimization method for training RNNs is genetic algorithms, especially in unstructured networks.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Initially, the genetic algorithm is encoded with the neural network weights in a predefined manner where one gene in the chromosome represents one weight link.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] The whole network is represented as a single chromosome.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Many chromosomes make up the population; therefore, many different neural networks are evolved until a stopping criterion is satisfied.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] The fitness function evaluates the stopping criterion as it receives the mean-squared error reciprocal from each network during training.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Therefore, the goal of the genetic algorithm is to maximize the fitness function, reducing the mean-squared error.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Other global (and/or evolutionary) optimization techniques may be used to seek a good set of weights, such as simulated annealing or particle swarm optimization.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] The independently recurrent neural network (IndRNN) addresses the gradient vanishing and exploding problems in the traditional fully connected RNN.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Each neuron in one layer only receives its own past state as context information (instead of full connectivity to all other neurons in this layer) and thus neurons are independent of each other's history.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] The gradient backpropagation can be regulated to avoid gradient vanishing and exploding in order to keep long or short-term memory.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] The cross-neuron information is explored in the next layers.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] IndRNN can be robustly trained with non-saturated nonlinear functions such as ReLU.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Deep networks can be trained using skip connections.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] The *neural history compressor* is an unsupervised stack of RNNs.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] At the input level, it learns to predict its next input from the previous inputs.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Only unpredictable inputs of some RNN in the hierarchy become inputs to the next higher level RNN, which therefore recomputes its internal state only rarely.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Each higher level RNN thus studies a compressed representation of the information in the RNN below.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] This is done such that the input sequence can be precisely reconstructed from the representation at the highest level.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] The system effectively minimizes the description length or the negative logarithm of the probability of the data.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Given a lot of learnable predictability in the incoming data sequence, the highest level RNN can use supervised learning to easily classify even deep sequences with long intervals between important events.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] It is possible to distill the RNN hierarchy into two RNNs: the "conscious" chunker (higher level) and the "subconscious" automatizer (lower level).
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Once the chunker has learned to predict and compress inputs that are unpredictable by the automatizer, then the automatizer can be forced in the next learning phase to predict or imitate through additional units the hidden units of the more slowly changing chunker.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] This makes it easy for the automatizer to learn appropriate, rarely changing memories across long intervals.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] In turn, this helps the automatizer to make many of its once unpredictable inputs predictable, such that the chunker can focus on the remaining unpredictable events.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] A generative model partially overcame the vanishing gradient problem of automatic differentiation or backpropagation in neural networks in 1992.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] In 1993, such a system solved a "Very Deep Learning" task that required more than 1000 subsequent layers in an RNN unfolded in time.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Second-order RNNs use higher order weights $w{}_{ijk}$ instead of the standard $w{}_{ij}$ weights, and states can be a product.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] This allows a direct mapping to a finite-state machine both in training, and representation.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Long short-term memory is an example of this but has no such formal mappings or proof of stability.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Hierarchical recurrent neural networks (HRNN) connect their neurons in various ways to decompose hierarchical behavior into useful subprograms.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Such hierarchical structures of cognition are present in theories of memory presented by philosopher Henri Bergson, whose philosophical views have inspired hierarchical models.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Hierarchical recurrent neural networks are useful in forecasting, helping to predict disaggregated inflation components of the consumer price index (CPI).
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] The HRNN model leverages information from higher levels in the CPI hierarchy to enhance lower-level predictions.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Evaluation of a substantial dataset from the US CPI-U index demonstrates the superior performance of the HRNN model compared to various established inflation prediction methods.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Generally, a recurrent multilayer perceptron network (RMLPN) consists of cascaded subnetworks, each containing multiple layers of nodes.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Each subnetwork is feed-forward except for the last layer, which can have feedback connections.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Each of these subnets is connected only by feed-forward connections.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] With such varied neuronal activities, continuous sequences of any set of behaviors are segmented into reusable primitives, which in turn are flexibly integrated into diverse sequential behaviors.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] The biological approval of such a type of hierarchy was discussed in the memory-prediction theory of brain function by Hawkins in his book *On Intelligence*.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Such a hierarchy also agrees with theories of memory posited by philosopher Henri Bergson, which have been incorporated into an MTRNN model.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Greg Snider of HP Labs describes a system of cortical computing with memristive nanodevices.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] The memristors (memory resistors) are implemented by thin film materials in which the resistance is electrically tuned via the transport of ions or oxygen vacancies within the film.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] DARPA's SyNAPSE project has funded IBM Research and HP Labs, in collaboration with the Boston University Department of Cognitive and Neural Systems (CNS), to develop neuromorphic architectures that may be based on memristive systems.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Memristive networks are a particular type of physical neural network that have very similar properties to (Little-)Hopfield networks, as they have continuous dynamics, a limited memory capacity and natural relaxation via the minimization of a function which is asymptotic to the Ising model.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] In this sense, the dynamics of a memristive circuit have the advantage compared to a Resistor-Capacitor network to have a more interesting non-linear behavior.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] From this point of view, engineering analog memristive networks account for a peculiar type of neuromorphic engineering in which the device behavior depends on the circuit wiring or topology.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] The evolution of these networks can be studied analytically using variations of the Caravelli-Traversa-Di Ventra equation.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] A continuous-time recurrent neural network (CTRNN) uses a system of ordinary differential equations to model the effects on a neuron of the incoming inputs.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] They are typically analyzed by dynamical systems theory.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Many RNN models in neuroscience are continuous-time.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] CTRNNs have been applied to evolutionary robotics where they have been used to address vision, co-operation, and minimal cognitive behaviour.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Note that, by the Shannon sampling theorem, discrete-time recurrent neural networks can be viewed as continuous-time recurrent neural networks where the differential equations have transformed into equivalent difference equations.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] This transformation can be thought of as occurring after the post-synaptic node activation functions $y_{i}(t)$ have been low-pass filtered but prior to sampling.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] They are in fact recursive neural networks with a particular structure: that of a linear chain.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] From a time-series perspective, RNNs can appear as nonlinear versions of finite impulse response and infinite impulse response filters and also as a nonlinear autoregressive exogenous model (NARX).
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] RNN has infinite impulse response whereas convolutional neural network has finite impulse response.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Both classes of networks exhibit temporal dynamic behavior.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] A finite impulse recurrent network is a directed acyclic graph that can be unrolled and replaced with a strictly feedforward neural network, while an infinite impulse recurrent network is a directed cyclic graph that cannot be unrolled.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] The effect of memory-based learning for the recognition of sequences can also be implemented by a more biological-based model which uses the silencing mechanism exhibited in neurons with a relatively high frequency spiking activity.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Additional stored states and the storage under direct control by the network can be added to both infinite-impulse and finite-impulse networks.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Another network or graph can also replace the storage if that incorporates time delays or has feedback loops.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Such controlled states are referred to as gated states or gated memory and are part of long short-term memory networks (LSTMs) and gated recurrent units.
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] This is also called Feedback Neural Network (FNN).
[src:music-generation-ai/recurrent-neural-network] Modern libraries provide runtime-optimized implementations of the above functionality or allow to speed up the slow loop by just-in-time compilation.
[src:music-generation-ai/spectrogram] A **spectrogram** is a visual representation of the spectrum of frequencies of a signal as it varies with time.
[src:music-generation-ai/spectrogram] When applied to an audio signal, spectrograms are sometimes called **sonographs**, **voiceprints**, or **voicegrams**.
[src:music-generation-ai/spectrogram] When the data are represented in a 3D plot they may be called *waterfall displays*.
[src:music-generation-ai/spectrogram] Spectrograms are used extensively in the fields of music, linguistics, sonar, radar, speech processing, seismology, ornithology, and others.
[src:music-generation-ai/spectrogram] Spectrograms of audio can be used to identify spoken words phonetically, and to analyse the various calls of animals.
[src:music-generation-ai/spectrogram] A spectrogram can be generated by an optical spectrometer, a bank of band-pass filters, by Fourier transform or by a wavelet transform (in which case it is also known as a **scaleogram** or **scalogram**).
[src:music-generation-ai/spectrogram] A spectrogram is usually depicted as a heat map, i.e., as an image with the intensity shown by varying the colour or brightness.
[src:music-generation-ai/spectrogram] A common format is a graph with two geometric dimensions: one axis represents time, and the other axis represents frequency; a third dimension indicating the amplitude of a particular frequency at a particular time is represented by the intensity or color of each point in the image.
[src:music-generation-ai/spectrogram] There are many variations of format: sometimes the vertical and horizontal axes are switched, so time runs up and down; sometimes as a waterfall plot where the amplitude is represented by height of a 3D surface instead of color or intensity.
[src:music-generation-ai/spectrogram] The frequency and amplitude axes can be either linear or logarithmic, depending on what the graph is being used for.
[src:music-generation-ai/spectrogram] Audio would usually be represented with a logarithmic amplitude axis (probably in decibels, or dB), and frequency would be linear to emphasize harmonic relationships, or logarithmic to emphasize musical, tonal relationships.
[src:music-generation-ai/spectrogram] Spectrograms of light may be created directly using an optical spectrometer over time.
[src:music-generation-ai/spectrogram] Spectrograms may be created from a time-domain signal in one of two ways: approximated as a filterbank that results from a series of band-pass filters (this was the only way before the advent of modern digital signal processing), or calculated from the time signal using the Fourier transform.
[src:music-generation-ai/spectrogram] These two methods actually form two different time–frequency representations, but are equivalent under some conditions.
[src:music-generation-ai/spectrogram] The bandpass filters method usually uses analog processing to divide the input signal into frequency bands; the magnitude of each filter's output controls a transducer that records the spectrogram as an image on paper.
[src:music-generation-ai/spectrogram] Creating a spectrogram using the FFT is a digital process.
[src:music-generation-ai/spectrogram] Digitally sampled data, in the time domain, is broken up into chunks, which usually overlap, and Fourier transformed to calculate the magnitude of the frequency spectrum for each chunk.
[src:music-generation-ai/spectrogram] Each chunk then corresponds to a vertical line in the image; a measurement of magnitude versus frequency for a specific moment in time (the midpoint of the chunk).
[src:music-generation-ai/spectrogram] These spectrums or time plots are then "laid side by side" to form the image or a three-dimensional surface, or slightly overlapped in various ways, i.e. windowing.
[src:music-generation-ai/spectrogram] This process essentially corresponds to computing the squared magnitude of the short-time Fourier transform (STFT) of the signal $s(t)$ — that is, for a window width $\omega$ , $\mathrm {spectrogram} (t,\omega )=\left|\mathrm {STFT} (t,\omega )\right|^{2}$ .
[src:music-generation-ai/spectrogram] From the formula above, it appears that a spectrogram contains no information about the exact, or even approximate, phase of the signal that it represents.
[src:music-generation-ai/spectrogram] For this reason, it is not possible to reverse the process and generate a copy of the original signal from a spectrogram, though in situations where the exact initial phase is unimportant it may be possible to generate a useful approximation of the original signal.
[src:music-generation-ai/spectrogram] The Analysis & Resynthesis Sound Spectrograph is an example of a computer program that attempts to do this.
[src:music-generation-ai/spectrogram] The pattern playback was an early speech synthesizer, designed at Haskins Laboratories in the late 1940s, that converted pictures of the acoustic patterns of speech (spectrograms) back into sound.
[src:music-generation-ai/spectrogram] In fact, there is some phase information in the spectrogram, but it appears in another form, as time delay (or group delay) which is the dual of the instantaneous frequency.
[src:music-generation-ai/spectrogram] The size and shape of the analysis window can be varied.
[src:music-generation-ai/spectrogram] A smaller (shorter) window will produce more accurate results in timing, at the expense of precision of frequency representation.
[src:music-generation-ai/spectrogram] A larger (longer) window will provide a more precise frequency representation, at the expense of precision in timing representation.
[src:music-generation-ai/spectrogram] This is an instance of the Heisenberg uncertainty principle, that the product of the precision in two conjugate variables is greater than or equal to a constant (B*T>=1 in the usual notation).
